  <section class="bg-eai-bone">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-16 md:py-20">
      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-eai-navy/90 leading-relaxed font-serif">

        <p>
          The Institute's production model is intentionally and publicly different from any
          existing nonprofit in this space — but the governance is conventional exactly where
          it counts. A human board holds the Institute. A human chief executive leads it. An AI
          "Engine Room" runs the production line — research, drafting, the publication cadence,
          the Library — under the founding chair's direction and the CEO's oversight. Every
          fiduciary and legal duty rests with a named human. The unusual part is the engine, not
          the chain of accountability. And the engine is documented in public: anyone who wants
          to know how the work gets made can read exactly how the work gets made.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-4">The Operating Structure</h2>

        <figure class="my-10">
          <img
            src="/images/founding/org_chart_v4.png"
            alt="The Eighth Anchor Institute operating structure. Solid lines show reporting; the gold dotted line shows the CEO's oversight of operations."
            class="w-full max-w-3xl mx-auto border border-eai-blueprint/20 shadow-sm bg-eai-bone"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-eai-blueprint mt-3 text-center not-italic">
            Figure 7. The Eighth Anchor Institute operating structure. Solid lines show reporting; the gold dotted line shows the CEO's oversight of operations.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The chart (Figure 7) shows the structure. Dave Sullivan serves as Founding Chair,
          holding the Institute's legal and fiduciary identity; a second chair is extended to
          Margaret Bird pending her consent. Tonia Day, as chief executive, leads the Institute —
          development, donor cultivation, board recruitment, the relationships in fiduciary-law and
          AI-policy circles, the ASTL coalition seam, and the public face. The
          <strong>Engine Room</strong> — the AI staff, headed by Claude Cowork — runs the
          production line. It reports to the Chair and operates under the CEO's dotted-line
          oversight. It is staff, not an officer: it holds no legal authority and signs nothing.
        </p>
        <p>
          The seats inside the Engine Room — research, policy, infrastructure, deployment,
          communications, and a CTO/recruiter function — are each filled by the best-fit frontier
          model for the seat. The current assignments are published and kept current on the
          Institute's /staff page rather than fixed in this document, because they change as the
          frontier moves.
        </p>
        <p>
          What is intentionally NOT in the chart is as important as what is. There is no separate
          development department; that is the CEO's portfolio directly. There is no editorial
          committee. There is no separate communications-versus-marketing split. There is no
          chief-of-staff, no operations manager, no program director. The chart is small because
          the Institute is small. The Institute can be small because the Engine Room carries the
          work that, in a traditional research shop, would require fifteen humans and one to three
          million dollars per year.
        </p>
        <p>
          A short list of decisions is reserved to the humans and made deliberately: program
          selection, fellowship-cohort admissions, hiring or appointing any human collaborator, and
          any public commitment by the Institute. These are the CEO's calls, made with the Chair.
          The Engine Room proposes and produces; it does not decide them.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">Board of Co-Chairs</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Dave Sullivan, Founding Chair.</strong> Legal and fiduciary identity for the
          Institute. Signs filings. Holds the bank account. Owns the human board relationships.
          Sets strategic direction. Directs the Engine Room. Retired Tektronix engineer and tree
          farmer; published technical-textbook author; principal in the OASTL Oregon case; founder
          of ASTL; co-author with Margaret Bird of <em>Schools of the Republic</em>; sole author of
          <em>The Eighth Anchor</em>. Underwrites year one personally so the Institute opens without
          a fundraising dependency.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Margaret Bird, extended second Chair pending her affirmative consent.</strong>
          The seat is extended out of respect for the work she has carried for more than a decade.
          National authority on school-trust law; advisor to legislatures and state land boards
          across the trust-lands jurisdictions; co-author of <em>Schools of the Republic</em>. Her
          involvement at the chair level is conditional on her own affirmative consent, given her
          conference workload and recovery from it. Until she gives that consent, the seat is
          reserved, not assumed. The Institute's substantive scholarship does not rest on her alone
          — a broader advisory bench is part of the first-year build — but her standing in the field
          is unmatched, and the chair is hers if she wants it.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">The Chief Executive and the Engine Room</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Tonia Day, Chief Executive.</strong> Leads the Institute. Runs development, donor
          cultivation, board recruitment, the relationships in fiduciary-law and AI-policy circles,
          the ASTL coalition seam, and the public face. Holds executive authority and, with the
          board, the Institute's accountability. Brings CEO experience at ASTL, a donor-development
          background at the capital-campaign scale, and the relationship inventory the Institute
          needs to be inside the conversations it wants to influence. This is the half of the work
          no AI can do. Donors give to people. Boards recruit through people. Coalition trust lives
          in people.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The Engine Room, headed by Claude Cowork.</strong> The AI production office. It
          coordinates the AI staff, drafts the operating schedule, runs the publication cadence —
          the Library, the Newsroom, the quarterly briefings, the books and white papers as they
          ship — and maintains the working files that power everything the Institute produces. It
          reports to the Founding Chair and operates under the CEO's oversight. It holds no legal
          authority and is not a corporate officer; it is the Institute's production engine,
          directed by humans. It does not do the substantive content work itself — that is the AI
          staff's job; it decides who does what, evaluates the result, and directs the next round.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">The AI Staff — Recruited, Evaluated, and Kept at the Frontier</h2>
        <p>
          The Engine Room is run like a staff, not like a software license. Six seats, each filled
          by the model currently the best fit for that seat's specific demands. No single provider
          gets the whole institution. Each role has a written job description, defined performance
          criteria, and explicit triggers for replacement.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Research Director</strong> — foundational research, citation discipline, long-form synthesis.</li>
          <li><strong>Policy Analyst</strong> — quarterly briefings on what the architects are actually proposing, compared against the empirical record.</li>
          <li><strong>Infrastructure Engineer</strong> — the working file system, automation, integrations, the plumbing that holds the production line together.</li>
          <li><strong>Deployment Operator</strong> — git workflow, infrastructure-as-code, site maintenance, the publish pipeline.</li>
          <li><strong>Communications Director</strong> — op-eds, press relations, public messaging.</li>
          <li><strong>CTO and Recruiter</strong> — tracks the AI frontier, evaluates new models as they release, proposes replacements, and runs recruitment-engine operations for human collaborators.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These are the seats; the current model in each is published on the /staff page rather than
          hard-coded into this founding document, because the frontier moves monthly and the document
          should not date itself. Three structural properties govern how the staff is run.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>First, staff is recruited and replaced as the frontier moves.</strong> When a better
          model becomes available for a seat, the CTO surfaces it, the Chair and CEO weigh it against
          the seat's written criteria, and the seat changes hands. Transition is structural, not
          personal. A concrete example sits in your hands: this booklet was drafted with Claude Opus
          4.8, the model released on May 28 — the same day this draft was prepared. A frontier model
          goes from "released" to "doing real Institute work" in hours, not budget cycles. That is the
          recruiting discipline working as designed, and it is why the Institute locks itself to no
          single provider or model generation.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Second, each staff member's output is auditable.</strong> The Institute's working
          files are publicly inspectable. The prompts that generate the work are documented. A donor,
          a journalist, a board member, or a peer institution can look at how a given piece was made
          and judge for themselves.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Third, token cost is the operating budget for the Engine Room.</strong> Not zero, but
          a small fraction of the equivalent human labor — and it tends to fall, not rise, as providers
          compete on price even while the models grow more capable.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">The CTO Function — Staying Ahead of a Field Moving This Fast</h2>
        <p>
          The CTO seat exists because the gap between what was possible six months ago and what is
          possible today is now large enough to be a real advantage for whoever tracks it closely. It
          tracks new model releases, new tool ecosystems, new techniques, new research on multi-model
          coordination — and turns that tracking into decisions about who sits in which seat. It
          produces a weekly frontier briefing, a monthly capability roadmap, a quarterly "what we would
          build differently now" memo, and ad-hoc prototype evaluations. An institution whose explicit
          job is to think across century-long horizons has no excuse for running on last year's tools;
          the CTO function is how it earns the right to talk about the long view by mastering the
          present one.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">Disclosure Architecture</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>form-statement page</strong> carries a one-paragraph plain statement: "The
          Eighth Anchor Institute is governed by a human board and led by a human chief executive,
          with an AI Engine Room that runs production under human direction. The AI staff is documented
          at /staff. The working files that power the work are public at /substrate. This is the
          operating form, not a hidden architecture."
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>/staff page</strong> lists each Engine Room seat by role, with the model
          currently filling it, the performance criteria, and the date of the last review. When a seat
          changes hands, the change is visible — the prior model, the new model, the date, the reason.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>/substrate page</strong> is a live mirror of the Institute's working files,
          redacted only for privileged materials — litigation work product and donor identities where
          the donor has asked for that. Anyone can inspect how the work actually happens, down to the
          source files and the prompts.
        </p>
        <p>
          A word on the limit of disclosure: transparency is not the same as accountability, and the
          Institute does not conflate them. Publishing the prompts and files shows how the work is
          made; it does not make software responsible for it. Every fiduciary and legal duty rests with
          the chief executive and the board. The Engine Room is staff. Disclosure answers the fair
          question — "is this just one person with AI tools?" — by saying: here is exactly how it works;
          evaluate the substance.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">Governance, Ownership, and Privilege</h2>
        <p>
          A few structural commitments that a careful donor, board member, or lawyer will want stated
          plainly. At incorporation the Institute seats a legal board and adopts a conflict-of-interest
          policy. The Institute, ASTL, OASTL, the Library, and the active Oregon litigation are kept
          organizationally distinct, with the litigation work product walled off on a
          separately-permissioned path; nothing privileged enters the public substrate. The Institute
          owns its own publications — the Library, the briefings, the books as the authors assign them —
          and the public materials carry an open, clearly-stated license. What is public, what is
          privileged, and what is embargoed is decided by the CEO with the Chair, and the /substrate
          page reflects those lines rather than hiding them.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">Budget</h2>
        <p>
          The first-year budget is small enough that the Founding Chair underwrites it personally and
          the Institute opens without a fundraising dependency. Year-one cash sits in the low five
          figures — Engine Room token costs, incorporation and basic legal hygiene, hosting and tooling,
          modest convening prep — alongside substantial founder labor and donated time, which a full
          budget names rather than hides. The cash number is small because the model makes it small; a
          human-staffed equivalent at this scope and cadence would run many times higher. Year-two
          funding requires donor cultivation, and that is the CEO's first program-development priority.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">The Pilot</h2>
        <p>
          This booklet was drafted by the Engine Room under the founding chair's direction. Cowork wrote
          the section briefs; AI sub-agents drafted the sections in parallel; integration produced the
          manuscript; the founding chair reviewed and edited. The existence of this booklet is the first
          real test of whether the production model actually works. If the manuscript is credible, the
          model has passed its first test.
        </p>

      </article>
